(712, 1, '2013-06-28 13:24:34', '2013-06-28 18:24:34', 'There are many things to consider when designing a new website. While clients may be focused on aesthetic values like color or animated image sliders, a designer is thinking about function and user experience and how those aspects are related to the potential design. In large design firms there are teams of people that include designers, developers, and user experience professionals. However, many freelancers are taking on all three of these roles simultaneously and need to develop a workflow that meets the client’s expectations for design and user experience. How is designing for ux and workflow done efficiently using traditional applications like Photoshop to present each aspect needed, while being efficient and following current design standards and best practices? Generally referred to as a Front End Developer, how does this person distinguish between standards of best practice and trends that may rapidly change?\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nTraditionally, workflow in teams consists of a designer creating the comp, or comprehensive image, for a website using Photoshop. With Photoshop a color palette and typography  is chosen, graphic elements are constructed, and the layout is established. The comp is presented to the client for approval, it’s then turned over to a developer who writes the code and builds the website in the browser (Frost, 2013). For the solo practitioner, or Front End Developer, this isn’t necessarily the most efficient way to design a website. The draw backs to presenting comps designed in Photoshop are that browsers display websites differently, and Photoshop can give clients a false sense that the finished website will look exactly as it does in a design comp. And while Photoshop can mimic rollover effects and provide basic navigation, it can’t recreate user experience like an actual website (Frost, 2013).\r\n\r\nCurrent trends suggest that websites should be designed in the browser rather than in Photoshop for this very reason. And with more and more Front End Developers paying attention to usability and user experience, designing in the browser might be the best way to accomplish good UX design. But not all traditional methods of design are being abandoned. Many authorities in user experience still advocate for sketching and paper prototyping in the early stages of design:\r\n<blockquote>Although starting a prototype on a computer is sometimes easier, it’s not the best way to visually problem-solve. When you need to ideate website layouts or mobile applications or to storyboard workflows and context scenarios, sketching is much more efficient. It keeps you from getting caught up in the technology, and instead focuses you on the best possible solution, freeing you to take risks that you might not otherwise take (Buick, 2011).</blockquote>\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-715" alt="Angela J. Holden Website Design | PSD vs. the Browser - Sketch" src="http://angelajholden.com/ajh/wp-content/uploads/psd-vs-browser-sketch.jpg" width="750" height="1004" />\r\n\r\nBuick (2011) goes on to explain that sketching is not the same as drawing, and makes the point that the more a designer sketches, the better he or she will become at it, ultimately making it an extremely effective communication tool for website design.\r\n\r\nSo how does the Front End Developer present their ideas to a client if they aren’t using Photoshop to create comps? Surely they aren’t presenting sketches to clients, but they aren’t starting to design in the browser until a design has been approved either. What is the balance between efficient workflow that presents clear, usable designs prior to the development phase of designing a website, that bypasses what was traditionally done in Photoshop? One aspect of the early stages of website design is wireframing. This is usually the next step after a sketch or paper prototype, and its focus is structure, layout, and basic usability. It’s the skeleton of the proposed website.\r\n\r\nRather than designing full comps using Photoshop, there are a variety of online tools for wireframing and prototyping that do a better job presenting ideas to clients before development begins. There are also numerous templates designed to be used in Photoshop that create wireframes and mood boards rather than comps that mimic a website. The idea being that more savvy clients will understand why designs are being presented in this way, and that less savvy clients need to be educated on new technology and best practices.\r\n\r\nThere are more tools available for wireframing and prototyping than I can discuss in this post. For a list of resources, I’ll direct your attention to an article on Smashing Magazine called “<a href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2010/02/05/50-free-ui-and-web-design-wireframing-kits-resources-and-source-files/" target="_blank">50 Free UI and Web Design Wireframing Kits, Resources and Source Files</a>.”\r\n\r\nOne tool that is worth pointing out is the immensely popular Style Tiles:\r\n<blockquote>Style tiles are for when a moodboard is too vague and a comp is too literal. Style tiles establish a direct connection with actual interface elements without defining layout. They work well for clients who have established brands and need them to translate smoothly to the web. Whereas the word “mood” is often associated with brand and identity design, the word “style” was chosen to mirror “cascading stylesheets” and reinforce that Style Tiles are specific to Web design (Warren, 2012).</blockquote>\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-716" alt="Angela J. Holden Website Design | PSD vs. the Browser - Style Tile" src="http://angelajholden.com/ajh/wp-content/uploads/Ed-StyleTile-blog.jpg" width="960" height="715" />\r\n\r\nWarren explains that interior designers don’t actually design rooms as comps for clients, so why should Front End Developers design a website, whether in Photoshop or in the browser, in order to present ideas for approval (Warren, 2012)? Her solution also implies designers and developers can be better communicators with clients through this tool. In order to convince a client of a concept or idea without actually showing them a website comp, Front End Developers will need excellent communication skills to sell their ideas. And interestingly enough, Style Tiles are a template for use in Photoshop.\r\n\r\nDan Rose (2013) also tries to help us understand where Photoshop fits in to our workflow by identifying the browser as a more efficient tool for web design:\r\n<blockquote>A workflow you may be familiar with is such: sketch, wireframe, produce the visual design in a graphics editor, develop said design in HTML and CSS. Skipping Photoshop assumes that we “design” in the HTML and CSS phase. The tricky part in doing that is determining what a suitable design deliverable is… Naturally, the question becomes, what do we do with Photoshop, now that we’re in the browser?</blockquote>\r\nDan Rose has been designing website comps in Photoshop since the 1990s and is an authority on Photoshop for this purpose. But he also recognizes that the shift away from Photoshop is more than a trend and insists there will always be “a need for discernible web design in Photoshop” (Photoshopetiquette.com, 2012). He’s even developed a set of rules, or etiquette, for designers to follow who continue to use Photoshop for their comps. These rules employ common sense, web standards, and best practices that take into account things like web typography, browser differences, image size, and how things like layers and file naming translates to a website being built in the browser (Photoshopetiquette.com, 2012).\r\n<h2>What does any of this have to do with usability or user experience?</h2>\r\nMost Front End Developers recognize that building a website is “an agile development process,” where there are “shifting objectives or newly added requirements” (Rogers, 2013). Workflows that demand agile, fluid, and usable processes aren’t served well by Photoshop’s static comps. Besides the issues with browser differences, Rogers (2013) points out that comps gives clients a false sense of usability. In his experience, using a tool like Style Tiles are good for selling design, but to sell usability, he has the client sign off on each phase of the development as its being done in the browser. He insists this can only be done after sufficient wireframing and that clients must be involved in each phase of the build. But ultimately says that it makes the development time much faster and more efficient when done this way:\r\n<blockquote>Doing the design directly in code allowed me, as a designer, to test the interactions immediately. This tightened the production cycle (design &gt; development &gt; test) and I could instantly make iterations on a single piece of functionality, changing it site-wide if necessary (Rogers, 2013).</blockquote>\r\nChris Coyier, founder of CSS-Tricks.com and an authority on Front End Development often talks about his use of Photoshop in the early stages of the design process. He speaks regularly at web development conferences about workflow and gave a great talk at BDConf in Dallas, TX that addressed this issue in 2012. He explains that he likes starting the design process in Photoshop because that’s what works for him. He goes on to say that using a design tool like Photoshop helps him feel more creative in the early stages, but appreciates and understands the importance of building and development in the browser. For Coyier, designing and writing code are two different things. He needs the freedom of a design tool to start a project and feel creative, and then he’ll write the code to make it happen in the browser.\r\n\r\nCoyier (2012) admits this doesn’t have anything to do with usability or wireframing, but rather says that Photoshop, when used purely as a design tool, still has an important place in the web design process. He insists it’s an excellent way to play with shapes, patterns, and color in order to inspire and feel creative when building a website.\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nWhether it’s a trend or best practice, it’s up to each of us to decide for ourselves how Photoshop fits into our design process. Front End Developers who successfully use Photoshop as a part of their workflow should not stop simply because the trend is to design in the browser. But for new developers who are creating a workflow, there are valid considerations to take into effect. How do you sell a usable design to clients and maintain an efficient and effective workflow? When you can answer that question, you’re doing the right thing whether you use Photoshop or not, in any part of your process.\r\n<h2>Works Citied</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Andrew, P. (2010, February 5). 50 Free UI and Web Design Wireframing Kits, Resources and Source Files | <cite>Smashing Magazine. Smashing Magazine For Professional Web Designers and Developers.</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2010/02/05/50-free-ui-and-web-design-wireframing-kits-resources-and-source-files/</li>\r\n	<li>Buick, P. (2011, December 13). The Messy Art Of UX Sketching | Smashing UX Design. <cite>Smashing UX Design | Usability, Psychology and Information Architecture.</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://uxdesign.smashingmagazine.com/2011/12/13/messy-art-ux-sketching/</li>\r\n	<li>Coyier, C. (Director) (2012, September 25). A Modern Web Designer''s Workflow. <cite>BDConf.</cite> Lecture conducted from Breaking Development, Dallas, TX. Retrieved May 5, 2013, from https://vimeo.com/50557334</li>\r\n	<li>Frost, B. (2013, January 21). The Post-PSD Era. <cite>Brad Frost Web.</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://bradfrostweb.com/blog/post/the-post-psd-era/</li>\r\n	<li>Rogers, J. (2013, April 29). Building a Better User Experience by Designing in the Browser | UX Magazine. <cite>UX Magazine | Defining and Informing the Complex Field of User Experience (UX).</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://uxmag.com/articles/building-a-better-user-experience-by-designing-in-the-browser</li>\r\n	<li>Rose, D. (2012). Photoshop Etiquette. <cite>Photoshop Etiquette.</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://photoshopetiquette.com/</li>\r\n	<li>Rose, D. (2013, April 22). Repurposing Photoshop For The Web | Smashing Magazine. <cite>Smashing Magazine For Professional Web Designers and Developers.</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://www.smashingmagazine.com/2013/04/22/repurposing-photoshop/?utm_source=feedly</li>\r\n	<li>Warren, S. (2012). Style Tiles. <cite>Style Tiles.</cite> Retrieved May 5, 2013, from http://styletil.es/</li>\r\n</ul>', 'PSD vs. the Browser: Designing for UX and Workflow', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'psd-vs-the-browser-designing-for-ux-and-workflow', '', '', '2013-07-10 11:56:56', '2013-07-10 16:56:56', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=712', 0, 'post', '', 0),
