(767, 1, '2013-07-10 10:22:42', '2013-07-10 15:22:42', 'With the popularity of icon fonts it seems natural to use them in our WordPress websites as well. And doing so could not be easier! If you aren’t already, I recommend that you use <a title="Icomoon Icon Fonts" href="http://icomoon.io/" target="_blank">Icomoon.io</a> to generate your icon fonts. If you’re new to icon fonts in general, or Icomoon in particular, Chris Coyier at CSS-Tricks does a wonderful job explaining them in this <a title="HTML for Icon Font Usage" href="http://css-tricks.com/html-for-icon-font-usage/" target="_blank">blog post</a> and in this <a title="Creating and Using a Custom Icon Font" href="http://css-tricks.com/video-screencasts/113-creating-and-using-a-custom-icon-font/" target="_blank">screencast.</a> This blog post picks up where Coyier leaves off and shows you how to add them to your WordPress navigation menu.<a title="Creating and Using a Custom Icon Font" href="http://css-tricks.com/video-screencasts/113-creating-and-using-a-custom-icon-font/" target="_blank">\r\n</a>\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-769" alt="Using Icon Fonts in WordPress Navigation | Angela J. Holden Website Design" src="http://angelajholden.com/ajh/wp-content/uploads/Icon-Fonts.png" width="850" height="235" />\r\n\r\nPay special attention to how you map your icons once selected. You shouldn’t ever map them to an actual letter, but rather to a symbol or the <a title="Mapping of Unicode characters | Private use characters" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mapping_of_Unicode_characters#Private_use_characters" target="_blank">Private Use Area</a> of the Unicode instead. I’ve done both, but I prefer to go with a straight use of the PUA rather than try to find symbols that match my icon. I think it’s just an easier approach, and if you use icon fonts correctly with Coyier’s markup, they’ll be nice and semantic and won’t break any accessibility rules.\r\n\r\nSo how do we get those icons into our WordPress navigation? After you select your icons and download the ZIP file from Icomoon, find the font folder and put it in your child theme. You’ll also get a style.css and index.html file.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-770" alt="Icon Font Files | Angela J. Holden Website Design" src="http://angelajholden.com/ajh/wp-content/uploads/Icon-Font-Files.png" width="535" height="92" />\r\n\r\nOpen the index.html file in your browser for a full list or your icons and their PUA codes. Next copy the following CSS from the style sheet and put it at the top of your child theme style sheet. As long as your font folder is in the child theme, you won’t have to change the file path in the <code>@font-face</code> rule in your CSS.\r\n<pre>@font-face {\r\n	font-family: ''AJH-Website-Design'';\r\n	src:url(''fonts/AJH-Website-Design.eot'');\r\n	src:url(''fonts/AJH-Website-Design.eot?#iefix'') format(''embedded-opentype''),\r\n		url(''fonts/AJH-Website-Design.woff'') format(''woff''),\r\n		url(''fonts/AJH-Website-Design.ttf'') format(''truetype''),\r\n		url(''fonts/AJH-Website-Design.svg#AJH-Website-Design'') format(''svg'');\r\n	font-weight: normal;\r\n	font-style: normal;\r\n}\r\n\r\n/* Use the following CSS code if you want to use data attributes for inserting your icons */\r\n[data-icon]:before {\r\n	font-family: ''AJH-Website-Design'';\r\n	content: attr(data-icon);\r\n	speak: none;\r\n	font-weight: normal;\r\n	font-variant: normal;\r\n	text-transform: none;\r\n	line-height: 1;\r\n	-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;\r\n}</pre>\r\nNext, Coyier tells us to use this HTML snippet\r\n<pre>&lt;span aria-hidden="true" data-icon="&amp;#xe999;"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</pre>\r\nwhich goes in the Navigation Label of our WordPress menu. If you aren’t sure where to put this, in the Dashboard go to Appearance &gt; Menus. Where you would normally have the name of each menu item like Home, Blog, About, etc., paste the HTML snippet before the name. Make sure you refer to the correct PUA code for the <code>[data-icon]</code> value. It’s probably something like <code>&amp;#xe000</code>. Save your menu and refresh your home page, and voila! You should have an icon next to your menu names.\r\n\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-768" alt="HTML for Icon Fonts | Angela J. Holden Website Design" src="http://angelajholden.com/ajh/wp-content/uploads/html-icon-fonts.png" width="635" height="828" />\r\n\r\nAt this point you’re probably noticing that square box in place of the icon code. That''s because your code is private and only applies to your icon font. And on the page, you''ll also notice the icon is sitting right next to the menu name. To give it some breathing room, we’ll add a little bit of padding on the right by dropping some code at the end of the <code>[data-icon]:before</code> selector in the child theme’s style sheet.\r\n<pre>[data-icon]:before {\r\n	font-family: ''AJH-Website-Design'';\r\n	content: attr(data-icon);\r\n	speak: none;\r\n	font-weight: normal;\r\n	font-variant: normal;\r\n	text-transform: none;\r\n	line-height: 1;\r\n	-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;\r\n padding-right: 10px;   /*Gives some padding to the right side of your Icon Font*/\r\n}</pre>\r\nNow save your menu and refresh the home page, and you should see it’s moved a comfortable distance away from the menu name. And that’s that!\r\n\r\nFor a great tutorial on using icon fonts with some fun CSS3 animations, check out this <a title="SIMPLE ICON HOVER EFFECTS" href="http://tympanus.net/codrops/2013/05/30/simple-icon-hover-effects/" target="_blank">Codrops</a> article.', 'Using Icon Fonts in WordPress Navigation', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'using-icon-fonts-in-wordpress-navigation', '', '', '2013-07-10 11:43:41', '2013-07-10 16:43:41', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=767', 0, 'post', '', 2),
