(1015, 1, '2013-12-01 16:50:08', '2013-12-01 22:50:08', 'I started learning about web design in 2010 when I took a Dreamweaver class at the local community college. I had been trying to figure out Dreamweaver for months, but I was thoroughly confused by HTML and CSS, and no online tutorial seemed to be simple enough for me to get it. I needed help. I needed a person, not a tutorial or a book, to ask questions and get feedback. I learned more about Dreamweaver in that evening than in the previous three months, and over the next couple of days I built my first website.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nI didn’t start learning WordPress until early 2012. I knew what a content management system was, but I had to be convinced they were better than static websites. Eighteen months later I’m designing and building WordPress themes for my clients, and I find myself in the unique position of being asked for help by WordPress newcomers. In fact, in the last week I’ve been contacted by several people asking if I could answer questions related to WordPress and web design. These requests inspired me to write a blog post outlining what I think is important, as well as the resources I use to be a better designer and business owner.\r\n\r\n<em>*All links referenced throughout are at the end of the article.</em>\r\n<h2>Hardware</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Computer: Dell Inspiron One with 23 inch touch monitor running Windows 8</li>\r\n	<li>Printer: Epson Artisan 725</li>\r\n	<li>Printer: HP Deskjet 1000</li>\r\n	<li>Microphone: MXL 900 USB</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe Dell Inspiron has a built in web cam that is quite nice, but does not have a built in microphone. I leave my MXL 990 plugged in at all times for online chats and to record screencasts. I use the keyboard that came with the computer, and I use a Microsoft wireless mouse.\r\n<h2>Software &amp; Apps</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Text Editor: Sublime Text 2</li>\r\n	<li>CSS &amp; Javascript Preprocessor: Prepros</li>\r\n	<li>FTP: Filezilla &amp; Expandrive</li>\r\n	<li>Graphics &amp; Image Editors: Adobe Photoshop, Illustrator, and InDesign</li>\r\n	<li>iOS Simulator: Microsoft Webmatrix</li>\r\n	<li>Screencasts: Snagit 11</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Sublime Text</h3>\r\nThese are the software applications I use almost every day to design and develop web sites and record tutorials for my clients. Sublime Text is the best text editor I’ve used, and it is my most used piece of software. A license costs $70.00 USD, but you can download a free trial and use it before you buy it. Trust me, it’s worth every penny.\r\n<h3>Prepros</h3>\r\nI started writing CSS in Sass/SCSS earlier this summer, and I use Prepros to compile and process all of my style sheets and Javascript files. If you aren’t familiar with this, I highly recommend you start learning to write in Sass or LESS and preprocess your CSS. It’s not drastically different from writing vanilla CSS, but it is a much better, more extensible language, and your style sheets will be far more organized. Prepros is free, open source software for both Mac and Windows, and it includes full Compass support.\r\n\r\nEverything about preprocessing is awesome, and you should jump in and start learning to do it as soon as possible. I’ll include resources at the end of this article on how you can get started with Sass (or LESS), and the apps available to use them.\r\n<h3>Filezilla &amp; Expandrive</h3>\r\nI use Filezilla to upload files via FTP, and I use Expandrive to connect to a live server and edit files. Filezilla is free, open source software, but Expandrive costs $40.00 USD after a 30 day free trial. Using FTP, however, is quickly becoming frowned upon in the design and development community in favor of version control. This is something I’m just starting to learn about and implement in my personal projects. Chris Coyier’s screencast called “Let’s Suck at Github Together” on CSS-Tricks is an excellent way to get started learning about version control, and I plan to use Github for all of my client work and personal projects by the end of 2013.\r\n<h3>Photoshop</h3>\r\nOf all Adobes products, I use Photoshop more than anything. Most of my design starts in Ps with basic design comps, and it’s in your best interest to learn the Ps features specific to web design for this reason. There’s been a lot of hot drama recently over designing in the browser versus designing in Photoshop. In my workflow, all design starts in Ps, and once approved by the client, I move it to the browser. Every one of us has to determine the workflow that best suits the client and the job, and this works for me on most projects.\r\n\r\nMy attitude about Photoshop comps is to treat them as mood boards for color, typography, assets, and basic layout. I don’t have time to code a design in the browser as a comp for clients. Photoshop makes this process faster and easier; and the better your Ps and CSS skills become, the better at designing comps you’ll be.\r\n<h3>Webmatrix (iOS Simulator)</h3>\r\nMicrosoft Webmatrix is free to download, and I use it for the iOS simulator. There are lots of ways to resize your browser window to see how your responsive designs behave, but an iOS simulator is both a smaller view and your site’s behavior on iOS for iPhone and iPad.\r\n<h3>Snagit</h3>\r\nSnagit is screen capture and recording software from Tech Smith. There’s a free 30 day trial, then a license will cost you about $50.00 USD. I record a lot of screencasts, from tutorials to usability tests, to private videos for clients and friends. I probably record something for someone at least three or four times a week, so this is a great tool for me. Tech Smith also has a free app called Jing to record short, five minute screencasts, or a more expensive option called Camtasia Studio for about $300.00 USD that includes video editing. In addition to screen recording, Snagit takes full screen captures which can be very handy.\r\n<h2>Skills</h2>\r\n<h3>Usability &amp; User Experience (UX)</h3>\r\nThese are the things, that in my opinion, you must understand to be a web designer. Design isn’t just about knowing HTML and CSS, or being good at Photoshop; it’s also about designing a website that is usable. You must have an understanding of usability and creating good user experiences (UX) to be an effective designer. I was very lucky to take a graduate level usability course when I worked on my master’s degree, because I guarantee that without the class, it would have taken me years to understand how important usability is. The best thing you can do for yourself and your clients is read Steve Krug’s “Don’t Make Me Think” to learn more about this important, and sometimes overlooked, aspect of web design.\r\n<h3>Content Strategy</h3>\r\nYou should develop an understanding of content strategy and working with content on the web. WordPress is, after all, a content management system, and web sites are above all else, words.\r\n\r\nPeople visit websites for information, and if content isn’t organized and well written, your job will be very difficult. Because how exactly do you design a web site without content? How do you determine layout, taxonomy, or any kind of structure without knowing what kind of content will be on the site? Plan to spend a tremendous amount of time educating your clients about content, and interviewing them to understand their business and their audience. You need to understand who will visit the website and what information they’ll be looking for. If your client can’t answer those questions, consider whether the job is right for you, and how effective your work will be without this information.\r\n<h3>HTML5</h3>\r\nYou must be very good at HTML5 and CSS. There is no way around this, because these two things are the framework for every web site. Dreamweaver is a wonderful tool, but if you can’t look at a Ps comp and at least write the HTML to match what you see, you need to stop what you’re doing and learn this skill. There is no shame in keeping your favorite HTML/CSS book at your side or on your lap as you work, but you must not rely on an HTML template from Dreamweaver as the backbone of every website you design. If it helps you get started because it includes all the great stuff you typically find in the &lt;head&gt;, that’s fine. But really, you should know what all of those things are and why they’re there anyway. And you don’t need Dreamweaver to get that information. I think you’re much better off using HTML5 Boilerplate as the starting point for any project.\r\n\r\nHTML5 is a gorgeously semantic markup language. It’s rich and provides so much meaning to content that when used properly, it will make your websites accessible and SEO friendly. Learn to write excellent HTML5. Understand when to use a &lt;section&gt; tag and when to use a &lt;div&gt;. Do not skimp on this because it is one of the most important skills you can have.\r\n<h3>CSS</h3>\r\nCSS is design. At the end of the day, CSS determines the look of your website in its entirety. We use CSS for layout, color, images, and behavior. I struggled with CSS for much longer than I care to admit, but I have finally reached a point in my personal development where I can write CSS with confidence–or at least without being terrified. That doesn’t mean I’m an expert or that I never have to Google how to achieve something using CSS, it just means that I am finally comfortable writing CSS to make my designs happen. The more I learn about CSS, the better I become as a designer. If you’re new to web design, plan to spend a long time–maybe even years–understanding CSS. You’ll probably never learn everything, but a very good foundation will be one of your greatest assets.\r\n<h3>Responsive Design</h3>\r\nCSS includes knowing responsive design, which at its core, is CSS applied to your designs when the browser is resized, or the site is being viewed on a device that is not a traditional computer. Learn everything you can about making your designs responsive, and what it means to design mobile first, if that’s appropriate for your client’s audience. If nothing else, understand that Google is paying attention to web sites that are (or aren’t) optimized for smartphone and tablet users, and be prepared to explain to your clients why you are (or aren’t) designing responsive web sites.\r\n\r\nNow that I’ve started designing my sites responsively, it’s no longer a question of whether or not the client wants to me pay me for responsive web design. It’s included in my price because that’s how I design. Period. There are sites in my portfolio that aren’t responsive because I made them or used a WordPress theme that was not responsive before I learned how to do it. Moving forward they’ll be replaced with mobile ready, responsive web sites.\r\n<h3>Learn about basic design concepts and principles</h3>\r\nJohn McWade was the first person to start desktop publishing IN THE WORLD. He is one of the best graphic designers–EVER–and his series of design books and guides from Before &amp; After Magazine are the best out there. McWade doesn’t teach illustration or how to use software, he teaches layout, color, and typography. His principles will help you better understand white space, choosing fonts, and applying color pallets to your web designs. There are conventions we follow as web designers that are specific to usability and user experience, but we still have a tremendous amount of freedom to make our designs unique and creative, and learning about basic design techniques is as important as learning HTML and CSS.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<h3>Books</h3>\r\nI own more web design books than I can possibly list here, but these are my favorites.\r\n\r\nThe Smashing Magazine\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>LibraryExcellent books from a great website, smashingmagainze.com</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA Book Apart Library\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A series of books that evolved from alistapart.com. I can’t recommend these enough. They are wonderfully engaging and perfect for all skills levels, especially beginners.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nDigging into WordPress\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Fantastic book about WordPress by Jeff Starr and Chris Coyier</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe Tao of WordPress\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Another terrific book about WordPress by Jeff Starr</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMurach’s HTML5 and CSS3\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>One of the best books you can own to learn HTML5 and CSS/CSS3. If you have any book at your side while you work, this should be the one.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBefore &amp; After Magazine: How to design cool stuff\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Both the books and subscription to the magazine are excellent resources for designers. McWade will get you thinking about typography, layout, and color in easy to follow tutorials.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Websites</h3>\r\nCSS-Tricks.com\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Chris Coyier is the creator of CSS-Tricks and his blog and screencasts have taught me more about web design than anything else. A subscription to “The Lodge” is well worth the $19.99 USD per month to watch his v10 redesign and mobile first design series. You’ll see him in think critically and run into the same problems we all have as web designers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTutsplus.com\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Tuts Plus runs a series of websites that covers everything from WordPress, Photoshop, Illustration, Development, and much, much more.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLynda.com\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Lynda is subscription based online tutorials from industry leaders in design and development. Over the last couple of years they’ve expanded to include videos on running a business to dealing with difficult people. Chris Coyier of CSS-Tricks recorded a tutorial about workflow and WordPress, and it is one of the best tutorials I’ve seen if you want to build your own WordPress themes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTympanus.net/codrops (Codrops)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Codrops is a playground for innovative design techniques centered around CSS and Javascript. They’re creative and fun and always include a demo and the source files. They’re also really good at gathering the web’s latest news and resources and combining them into a weekly resource called the “Collective”.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCodex.wordpress.org (WordPress Codex)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If you want to design and develop websites using WordPress, you will spend hours reading the WordPress Codex. Everything you want to know about WordPress is in the Codex, and you should read it early and often.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Podcasts</h3>\r\nThe web’s best workers are also podcasting. These are the podcasts I listen to to stay up to date on web standards, best practices, tips for running my business and technology in general.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Shop Talk Show</li>\r\n	<li>Boag World</li>\r\n	<li>BizCraft</li>\r\n	<li>The Tech Guy</li>\r\n	<li>Hello Monday</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nAre you overwhelmed yet? That’s okay! This is a lot of information. But quite frankly, most of this I only figured out in the last year, all while working full time and going graduate school. If I can do it, so can you.\r\n\r\nI could go on and on about what new web designers should learn to be better at building web sites, but these are just the things that work for me. I’m still a relatively new designer, or at least that’s how I see myself, and I’m learning new things every day; forming processes to suit my needs and my clients. Part of this journey will be for you to open your mind and your heart to the opportunities and people that will come into your life to help you learn and grow. Engage with fellow designers, be creative, and above all else, if you want to be good at building websites, then you should JUST BUILD WEBSITES. Build as many as you can, as often as you can, and you’ll be good at it sooner than you think.\r\n<h3>Links</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://tympanus.net/codrops/">http://tympanus.net/codrops/</a> - Codrops</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://tutsplus.com/">https://tutsplus.com/</a> - Tuts Plus</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.bamagazine.com/Default.asp">http://www.bamagazine.com/Default.asp</a> - Before &amp; After Magazine</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2013/06/changes-in-rankings-of-smartphone_11.html">http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2013/06/changes-in-rankings-of- smartphone_11.html</a> - Google &amp; Responsive Design/SEO</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.techsmith.com/">http://www.techsmith.com/</a> - Tech Smith/Snagit</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://css-tricks.com/video-screencasts/101-lets-suck-at-github-together/">http://css-tricks.com/video-screencasts/101-lets-suck-at-github-together/</a> - Let''s Suck at Github Together</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://css-tricks.com/">http://css-tricks.com/</a> - CSS-Tricks</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.expandrive.com/expandrive">http://www.expandrive.com/expandrive</a> - Expandrive</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://alphapixels.com/prepros/">http://alphapixels.com/prepros/</a> - Prepos</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.sublimetext.com/">http://www.sublimetext.com/</a> - Sublime Text</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/HP-2009M-20-Inch-LCD-Monitor/dp/B001UHOX2S">http://www.amazon.com/HP-2009M-20-Inch-LCD-Monitor/dp/B001UHOX2S</a> - HP Monitor</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.dell.com/us/p/inspiron-one-23-2330-aio/pd">http://www.dell.com/us/p/inspiron-one-23-2330-aio/pd</a> - Dell Inspiron</li>\r\n</ul>', 'How I Work', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'work', '', '', '2013-12-01 16:51:29', '2013-12-01 22:51:29', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1015', 0, 'post', '', 0),
