(1118, 1, '2014-01-16 12:07:07', '2014-01-16 18:07:07', '<h2>Launching the Site</h2>\r\nMy goal was to launch the site on October 31, 2013. It was important to me the site go live and I start getting feedback from my audience at least a full month before the project was due to be turned in. I finished building the theme by the middle of October, and I spent two and a half weeks just working with content. I was very happy I built this time for content into the project, because as I arranged and organized content, there were areas of the site that had to be modified, and I had plenty of time to make necessary adjustments. I also had time to review and edit each post.\r\n\r\nLate in the evening on October 31st, I launched the site. In my mind, it was only 95% ready, but I decided that I still had the next 30 days to make changes, get feedback, conduct a second round of usability testing, and write the reflection paper. After it went live, I posted updates on Facebook about the new site, I and went to bed. The next morning when I woke up, Team Say had shared the link on their Facebook page and the site received some very good traffic overnight. The feedback from other fans on Facebook was positive, and I was quite pleased.\r\n<h2>More Feedback from Fazil Say – November 3, 2013</h2>\r\nAt this point, I stopped working for several days to take care of some personal business. Fazil had been on a short tour in Japan and was just returning to Istanbul for more performances. Soon I received another message from him:\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<blockquote>fantastic Angela fantastic... i will contact eren</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nThat was followed by a message from a member of Fazil’s management, Eren Yagmuroglu, that Fazil really did love the site, and they would be in touch shortly with an article for me to publish.', 'Reflection Paper: Launching the Site and More Feedback from Fazil Say', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-launching-site-feedback-fazil-say', '', '', '2014-01-16 12:06:54', '2014-01-16 18:06:54', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1118', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1121, 1, '2014-01-16 12:08:03', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<span style="line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;">Two weeks after the launch, I began a second round of usability testing. I decided to use the same tasks for this round as I did for the first, and to compare those results. Of the five participants from the first round, only two were available for testing this time: Deb from California, and Cheryl from North Carolina. The three new participants were Babak, a graphic designer and Turkish-English translator from Azerbaijan, Donna, a legal assistant from Minnesota, and Melissa, a certified nursing assistant from Minnesota.</span>\r\n\r\nIn this round of testing, much to my dismay, search continued to be an issue. For aesthetic value, I put the search box at the bottom of the page in the footer, not an uncommon place to do so, yet nearly every participant commented that it should be at the top of the page near the navigation.\r\n\r\nAside from this, the participants completed all of the tasks without difficulty except for the task related to finding all articles about just one topic. Again, I hoped people would find a very prominent tag cloud in the sidebar, but the sidebar is only visible when visiting an article related section of the site. I used the term ‘archives’ in the navigation to indicate this was an archive of all the articles written, but only one participant knew what that meant. The task, specifically, was to find every article about a particular composition, so most participants clicked on the menu item ‘compositions’ to complete the task. This was an indicator of two things: first, that I should include links to articles related to compositions in the compositions section of the site, and to change the navigation from ‘archives’ to ‘articles’.\r\n\r\nIn general, I received user feedback about how surprising the improvements were. When I told people I was planning to redesign the site, I received many comments about how it should not be changed, or how it could not possibly be better than it was. I think that was a reaction to the old site’s visual appeal, because the more I learned about WordPress leading up to the redesign, the more displeased I was with the old site’s functionality. While I didn’t dislike the old site’s color and typography, I did want to create an original design, but my focus was on the site’s structure and functionality.', 'Reflection Paper: Usability Testing - New Site', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-usability-testing-new-site', '', '', '2014-01-16 12:08:03', '2014-01-16 18:08:03', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1121', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1123, 1, '2014-01-16 12:09:12', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<span style="line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;">The best part about this project is that it is personal, but not just because I love Fazil Say’s music. This is the type of work I want to do for a living, and I am passionate about doing it really well. I also went into this project knowing that when the redesign was complete, the real work to maintain it and continue creating content was just beginning. I have a place to try new techniques for layout, design, and content strategy with a diverse audience to give me feedback.</span>\r\n\r\nWith the exception of one class in the technical communication program, I am a self-taught web designer. I’ve been building websites for about four years, but I never really did it well. I’ve struggled to learn HTML and CSS, and the websites I built prior to this year reflected my lack of confidence and understanding of some basic concepts.\r\n\r\nOnce I entered the technical communication program, my eyes were immediately opened to new ideas and technologies. The biggest of those was my introduction to WordPress by Fred Carpenter in the Document Design class. That set me down a path of customizing WordPress themes for 18 months, and making many, many websites and working with lots of content. Eventually I started to understand how content should be written and organized, and then how to make sure a website is usable.\r\n\r\nEvery class in this program has contributed my development as a web designer, from a thorough knowledge of rhetoric and the power of language, to research theory and writing and becoming a critical researcher and content provider. But the two classes that catapulted my web design career were Usability Testing and Writing and Designing for the Web. I had been reading a lot about usability, but I didn’t understand its roll in web design or how significant it is. Creating personas, writing and conducting usability tests, and analyzing their results were an eye opening experience. It seems quite simple now, but I finally understood that websites are built for the people who use them, not for the designers who build them.\r\n\r\nDespite how much I already knew about web design and WordPress, I was not moving forward as a designer. I had stalled because I lacked a foundation in HTML and CSS, and I had become very impatient trying to learn the basics of these programming languages. But when I purchased the books required for the class, I immediately sat down and read the first four chapters of the textbook titled “Murach’s HTML5 &amp; CSS3”. In the first 100 pages of that book, I learned things about HTML and CSS that I had been struggling to understand for several years. I have purchased many books on these topics, and this book is, by far, the easiest to read and understand about web design. Throughout this class we used the examples and assignments in the book to build and modify websites, and I quickly took what I was learning and started building my designs.\r\n\r\nThis happened several months before I was ready to design the fansite, so I used this knowledge on small personal projects and client work. I was building a lot of confidence with each new project, and soon I was comfortably writing code and making web sites with HTML5 and CSS. The timing was incredible, because when I was ready to start the design phase of this project, I could focus on how to write my code for WordPress; not just how to write the code.\r\n\r\nGraduate school didn’t teach me everything I need to know about web design. It introduced me to new ideas and taught me to be a life-long learner. This has been one of the most positive experiences of my entire life, and to top it all off, I have a master’s degree to show for it. I am so grateful for the opportunity this program gave me to realize my potential in this field, and for encouraging me to do what I love.', 'Reflection Paper: Project Conclusion', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-project-conclusion', '', '', '2014-01-16 12:09:12', '2014-01-16 18:09:12', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1123', 0, 'post', '', 0),
